IFC - SMU Students:
Informed Consent Form

Title of Study: Do Canadians Understand the Risk of False Confessions? 


INTRODUCTION

My name is Dr. Marc Patry and I am a full-time faculty member in the Psychology Department at Saint Mary’s University and supervisor of this research project. Emily Rybak is the principal investigator in this research and is a current Master’s student at Saint Mary’s and Pierre-Olivier Couture is the co-investigator of this research and is a current Undergraduate student at Saint Mary’s University. This research has received partial internal funding. I would like to invite you to participate in this research study regarding the knowledge Canadian’s have concerning risks of false confessions during police interrogations. Undergraduate student participation in this study will not affect your course outcome in any way.



PURPOSE OF THIS RESEARCH 

This research aims to examine the level of knowledge that Canadians currently have regarding police interrogations, and any factors that may or may not contribute to those interrogations resulting in false confessions.



PARTICIPATION 

Anybody who is 19 or older and a Canadian Citizen may participate. You will be asked to follow a secure link online to complete this study on Qualtrics. As this is an online study, you may participate from the location of your choice. Participants will be asked to complete a short survey containing questions related to their knowledge of police interrogations and questions. The study is expected to last approximately 15 minutes.



POTENTIAL BENEFITS 

Benefits of this study may include contributing to psycho-legal research and potentially the legal system, by providing information regarding laypersons knowledge on an important topic. In addition, this study may benefit you by increasing your knowledge and awareness of interrogation and confession research.



POTENTIAL RISKS FOR PARTICIPANTS 

Some questions in this study could result in feelings of discomfort or emotional distress. Should you feel uncomfortable during this study, you are able to withdraw at any point without negative consequence. As a Saint Mary’s student, if you experience feelings of discomfort, we encourage you to utilize the free counseling services on campus. Counseling services are located on the fourth floor of the Saint Mary’s Student Center, should you wish to visit, or you can contact them by telephone at: 902-420-5615 or by email at: counselling@smu.ca. Should you wish to obtain help outside of the university, we encourage you to contact the Mental Health Mobile Crisis Team. This is a free service that assists anyone experiencing a mental health crisis or mental distress. The Mental Health Mobile Crisis Team can be reached at 1-888- 429-8167. You can also contact the Halifax mental health crisis support at 902-429-8167 or Eligible Saint Mary’s participants will receive .25% bonus points for the class of their choosing for participating in this study. SMU students need to complete the study through SONA in order to receive the bonus points. You also have the opportunity to be compensated for your participation by entering a prize draw to win a $25 gift card. If you would like to enter the draw for the $25 gift card you will be asked to provide your first name and telephone number after completing the main survey. You will be instructed to click on a link that takes you to a separate Qualtrics survey to fill out the Participation Prize Draw Form so that this information can be kept separate from the rest of the survey. Wellness Together Canada at 1-866-585-0445.



PARTICIPATION COMPENSATION 

Due to the collection of personal contact information for the prize draw, this information will not be anonymous, however it is subject to confidentiality. None of the information given on the Participation Prize Draw Form will be linked to your survey responses in any way.



CONFIDENTIALITY 

All of the information that you provide will be subject to confidentiality. Online data will be collected via Qualtrics and will be stored on Canadian servers. No personal identifiable information is being collected as part of the main survey and is therefore considered to be anonymous. Once data collection is complete the data will be downloaded and removed from the server. The data will be downloaded and stored on personal, password protected, computers belonging to the researchers. None of the data will be connected to any personal identifiers such as names.All downloaded data from the main study questionnaire will be stored in perpetuity following the dissemination of the project. Once the study and the prize draw has been completed, the confidential identifiable information from the prize draw survey will be destroyed in order to protect the personal contact information of the participants.



STUDY RESULTS 

On completion of the study the researchers will create a summary report. It is anticipated that this will be available by August 2024. This research is being conducted with the expectation that it will potentially lead to a publication as well as conference presentations. If you are interested in the study’s findings, please contact the researchers following the completion of the survey. If you contact the researchers indicating that you are interested in the study’s findings, your contact information will be confidentially saved and stored on personal, password protected, computers belonging to the researchers, and you will be contacted with the disseminated results when the study is complete. The researchers will also be disseminating the findings amongst the facilities that assisted in the recruitment of participants. Please note that as all the data from the main survey are anonymous, we cannot provide individualized results.



HOW CAN I WITHDRAW FROM THIS STUDY? 

Participants are free to withdraw from this research study at any time without penalty. Should you wish to withdraw during the study, you may simply exit the web browser. Participants who withdraw from the study are still eligible to enter the Prize Draw. Students recruited through SONA who choose to withdraw from the study will still receive the .25% bonus points. Upon submission of your survey, researchers will no longer be able to exclude your data from analyses, as we will not be collecting identifying information in the main survey and therefore will be unable to identify the data as yours.



QUESTIONS & CONTACT FOR CONCERNS 

Should you have any further questions about this study, please feel free to contact Emily Rybak (Emily.Rybak@smu.ca), Pierre-Olivier Couture (pierre-olivier.couture@smu.ca) or Dr. Marc Patry (Marc.Patry@smu.ca; 902-491-8605).

This research has been reviewed and cleared by the Saint Mary’s University Research Ethics Board. If you have any questions or concerns about ethical matters, you may contact the Saint Mary’s University Research Ethics board at ethics@smu.ca or (902) 420-5728; REB File# 23- 056).



CONSENT

Please know that by participating in this research, you are not giving up any legal rights in the event that you are harmed during the research. By clicking the button to begin the survey, I understand that my participation is voluntary, I can withdraw from this study at any time without penalty, and I agree to participate in this study, titled: Do Canadians Understand the Risk of False Confessions?

Debrief - SMU:
Participant Debriefing Form

Title of Research: Do Canadians Understand the Risk of False Confessions? 


Dear Participant,

We would like to thank you for your participation in this study. REB File# 23-056).

As a reminder, the purpose of this research is to examine the level of knowledge Canadian’s currently have regarding police interrogations and false confessions. Once all of the data is collected and analyzed for this project, we plan on sharing this information with the psycho-legal research community and hope to have it published.



If you are interested in receiving more information regarding the results of this study, or if you have any questions or concerns, please contact Dr. Marc Patry at marc.patry@smu.ca or 902-491-8605.



If you experience an adverse reaction due to your participation in this study, we would ask that you contact us at your soonest convenience. Any adverse reactions will be reported to the Research Ethics Board. If you are a student of Saint Mary’s University and you experienced feelings of discomfort, we encourage you to utilize the free counselling services on campus. Counselling services are located on the fourth floor of the Saint Mary’s Student Center, should you wish to visit, or you can contact them by telephone at: 902-420-5615 or by email at: counselling@smu.ca

Should you wish to obtain help outside of the university, we encourage you to contact the Mental Health Mobile Crisis Team. This is a free service that assists anyone experiencing a mental health crisis or mental distress. The Mental Health Mobile Crisis Team can be reached at 1-888- 429-8167. You can also contact the Halifax mental health crisis support at 902-429-8167 or Wellness Together Canada at 1-866-585-0445.





As with all Saint Mary's University projects involving human participants, this project was reviewed by the Saint Mary's University Research Ethics Board. Should you have any comments or concerns about ethical matters or would like to discuss your rights as a research participant, please contact the Chair of the Research Ethics Board at 902-420-5728 or ethics@smu.ca.



Thank you again for your participation in this study.

Q1_1: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - The average person can differentiate between when someone is telling the truth or lying.
Q1_2: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Compared to most adults, adolescents exhibit "immaturity of judgment" in their decision- making.
Q1_3: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - If police present a suspect with false evidence during an interrogation, it is more likely that the suspect will confess to a crime they did not commit.
Q1_4: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Compared to guilty suspects, innocent suspects are more likely to waive their charter rights.
Q1_5: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - In general, people's behavior is strongly influenced by their expectations of reward and punishment
Q1_6: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Trained police can distinguish between truths and lies at high levels of accuracy.
Q1_7: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Sleep deprivation affects decision making and makes a suspect vulnerable to influence.
Q1_8: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Explicit promises of leniency or immunity during interrogation can lead a person to confess to a crime that they did not commit.
Q1_9: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Police officer expressions of sympathy and moral justification for a crime can lead a suspect to believe that the police will be lenient with them when they confess to a crime.
Q1_10: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Misinformation about an event can change a person's memory for that event.
Q1_11: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Individuals who have intellectual disabilities are particularly vulnerable to the pressures of police.
Q1_12: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Observers tend to underestimate the effects of situational factors on the behavior of other people.
Q1_13: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - An average adult cannot be induced into giving a false confession.
Q1_14: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Individuals with compliant or suggestible personalities are particularly vulnerable to influence during an interrogation.
Q1_15: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Compared to adults, adolescents are more likely to give false confessions
Q1_16: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Authority figures can produce illicit acts of obedience from people through a step-by-step process of gradual escalation.
Q1_17: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - People can be trained to distinguish between truths and lies at high levels of accuracy by observing nonverbal symptoms of anxiety.
Q1_18: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - People can be trained to distinguish between truths and lies at high levels of accuracy by learning how to detect micro-expressions in the face.
Q1_19: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Individuals with diagnosed psychological disorders may be particularly vulnerable to influence during an interrogation.
Q2_1: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Threats of physical violence and punishment during interrogation can lead someone to confess to a crime he or she did not commit.
Q2_2: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Conducting an interview in a public place, as opposed to an interrogation room, will increase the risk that an innocent suspect would confess to a crime he or she did not commit
Q2_3: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - A confession must be true if it contains accurate details about the crime.
Q2_4: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Innocent people never give false confessions "voluntarily" -- without pressure from police.
Q2_5: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Charter rights to silence and to counsel provide an adequate safeguard against coercive interrogations.
Q2_6: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - The idea that someone can be induced to confess to a serious crime he or she did not commit is well known to laypeople as a matter of common sense.
Q2_7: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Enhanced interrogation techniques (i.e. torture) can lead an innocent person to confess or otherwise provide unreliable information.
Q2_8: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - In the absence of other evidence, people can distinguish between true and false confessions at high levels of accuracy
Q2_9: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Compared to guilty suspects, innocent suspects are more likely to waive their Charter rights.
Q2_10: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Compared to guilty suspects, innocent suspects are more likely to strongly protest during an interrogation
Q2_11: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - No group of professionals can reliably differentiate between true and false confessions.
Q2_12: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - Most jurors know enough about interrogation tactics and confessions to make informed judgements about the confession evidence in a criminal trial.
Q2_13: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - In a case where the truthfulness of a confession is disputed, jurors would benefit by hearing from a witness who is an expert on interrogation and confession.
Q2_14: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - It would be useful for jurors to hear an expert witness testify about interrogation techniques used by police.
Q2_15: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - It would be useful for jurors to hear an expert witness testify about why a defendant might falsely confess to a crime he or she did not commit.
Q2_16: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - If I were to listen to an audiotape of an interrogation and confession, I would be able to tell if the confession was true or false.
Q2_17: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - If I were to watch a videotape of an interrogation and confession, I would be able to tell if the confession was true or false.
Q2_18: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - If interrogated by the police, I would confess to a minor crime.
Q2_19: Please give your opinion on the following questions: - If interrogated by the police, I would confess to a serious crime.
